title: Senior Engineer
description: Three years of OCONUS support in the Site Systems Engineering (SSE) lab at JDFPG, Alice Springs Australia. Duties started as stay-behind engineer (hardware and software) for the Telemetry Analysis Sub-System (TASS), a large FISINT processing system, performing enhancements, upgrades, and problem troubleshooting, resolution and configuration control. Duties soon included X-Midas based QRC agile application development, integration and support to FIS and other mission areas. Supported early X-Midas baseline development by contributing primitives such as XRTSURFace, for 3D data visualization of X-Midas data files, and XRTSAMview, for visualizing contents of Texas Memory Systems (TMS) rapid access memory devices. Created the XSTL option tree (macros and primitives) that allowed visualization of and mouse control over the STL Digital Switch Matrixes. Created the TPLAID option tree that allowed automated signal platform classification of “T”-type signals. Also presented X-Midas training to local site personnel.
name: Kurt Hassler

title: Senior Engineer
description: Seven years of experience as a lead software developer, supporting design, development, integration and deployment of many efforts supporting National contracts. Many tasks involved programming real-time applications using specialized hardware (i.e. array processors); primarily in FISINT and ELINT domains. Most of these efforts were focused around the National Telemetry Processing Center (NTPC, now NSPC) (Peevey, Rissman, Rootstock, Rushhour), but also included system deliveries to third party countries (HEADSAIL II) and to the CAC Lab (MTEPP / RISE). Served as the sole Temporary Duty (TDY) engineer (software, hardware, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) infrastructure) for a multi-month deployment to a third party country (HEADSAIL II). Served as technical lead and Program Manager for an upgrade to an ELINT processing system (DENTIN). Supported an R&D effort to design, develop, configure and install ruggedized SIGINT processing systems on an Army platform (SHIELDS). Supported the development of a small FISINT system for treaty verification that was delivered to Russia (START) and served as lead Project Security for many of the above capabilities.
